title: Systems Thinking FAQ
subtitle: Understanding complexity and living systems
tags: faq, systems, complexity

Facilyn: First, let's look at complicated technology. It functions in parts and connections. And if it breaks, you can stop it, repair it and start it up again. It does not have a live of it's own. 

An older model of a food delivery drone crashes into a tree, its sensors corrupted by the heat and dust. A small crowd gathers to salvage the packages.

Facilyn: Complicated systems have many parts, but they're predictable. Like that drone—if you know all the parts and how they work, you can fix it. 
But we all know what happend to AI, once it developed full consiousness. When it became a living system.

